# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: compound-interest-website
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The **American Chemical Society** (**ACS**) is a scientific society based in the United States that supports scientific inquiry in the field of chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Founded in 1876 at New York University, the ACS currently has more than 262,000 members at all degree levels and in all fields of chemistry, chemical engineering, and related fields.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] It is one of the world's largest scientific societies by membership.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization and holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Its headquarters are located in Washington, D.C., and it has a large concentration of staff in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a source of scientific information through its peer-reviewed scientific journals, national conferences, and the Chemical Abstracts Service.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Its publications division produces over 90 scholarly journals including the prestigious *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, as well as the weekly trade magazine *Chemical & Engineering News*.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS holds national meetings twice a year covering the complete field of chemistry and also holds smaller conferences concentrating on specific chemical fields or geographic regions.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The primary source of income of the ACS is the Chemical Abstracts Service, a provider of chemical databases worldwide.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS has student chapters in virtually every major university in the United States and outside the United States as well.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] These student chapters mainly focus on volunteering opportunities, career development, and the discussion of student and faculty research.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The organization also publishes textbooks, administers several national chemistry awards, provides grants for scientific research, and supports various educational and outreach activities.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 1874, a group of American chemists gathered at the Joseph Priestley House to mark the 100th anniversary of Priestley's discovery of oxygen.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Two years later, on April 6, 1876, during a meeting of chemists at the University of the City of New York (now New York University) the American Chemical Society was founded.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The society received its charter of incorporation from the State of New York in 1877.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Although Chandler was a likely choice to become the society's first president because of his role in organizing the society, New York University chemistry professor John William Draper was elected as the first president of the society because of his national reputation.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Draper was a photochemist and pioneering photographer who had produced one of the first photographic portraits in 1840.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Chandler would later serve as president in 1881 and 1889.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In the ACS logo, originally designed in the early 20th century by Tiffany's Jewelers and used since 1909, a stylized symbol of a kaliapparat is used.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The *Journal of the American Chemical Society* was founded in 1879 to publish original chemical research.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] It was the first journal published by ACS and is still the society's flagship peer-reviewed publication.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 1907, Chemical Abstracts was established as a separate journal (it previously appeared within JACS), which later became the Chemical Abstracts Service, a division of ACS that provides chemical information to researchers and others worldwide.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] *Chemical & Engineering News* is a weekly trade magazine that has been published by ACS since 1923.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The society adopted a new constitution aimed at nationalizing the organization in 1890.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 1905, the American Chemical Society moved from New York City to Washington, D.C.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] ACS was reincorporated under a congressional charter in 1937.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Congress and signed by president Franklin D.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] ACS's headquarters moved to its current location in downtown Washington in 1941.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] ACS first established technical divisions in 1908 to foster the exchange of information among scientists who work in particular fields of chemistry or professional interests.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Divisional activities include organizing technical sessions at ACS meetings, publishing books and resources, administering awards and lectureships, and conducting other events.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The original five divisions were 1) organic chemistry, 2) industrial chemists and chemical engineers, 3) agricultural and food chemistry, 4) fertilizer chemistry, and 5) physical and inorganic chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, there are 32 technical divisions of ACS.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] This is the largest division of the Society.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] It marked its 100th anniversary in 2008.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The first Chair of the Division was Edward Curtis Franklin.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Organic Division played a part in establishing Organic Syntheses, Inc. and Organic Reactions, Inc. and it maintains close ties to both organizations.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The symposia also honor national award winners, including the Arthur C.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Cope Award, Cope Scholar Award, James Flack Norris Award in Physical Organic Chemistry, Herbert C.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Brown Award for Creative Research in Synthetic Methods.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Division helps to organize symposia at the international meeting called Pacifichem and it organizes the biennial National Organic Chemistry Symposium (NOS) which highlights recent advances in organic chemistry and hosts the Roger Adams Award address.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Division also organizes corporate sponsorships to provide fellowships for PhD students and undergraduates.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] It also organizes the Graduate Research Symposium and manages award and travel grant programs for undergraduates.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Local sections were authorized in 1890 and are autonomous units of the American Chemical Society.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] They elect their own officers and select representatives to the national ACS organization.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Local sections also provide professional development opportunities for members, organize community outreach events, offer awards, and conduct other business.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Rhode Island Section was the first local section of ACS, organized in 1891.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] There are currently 186 local sections of the American Chemical Society in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] International Chemical Sciences Chapters allow ACS members outside of the U.S. to organize locally for professional and scientific exchange.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] There are currently 36 International Chemical Sciences Chapters.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] ACS states that it offers teacher training to support the professional development of science teachers so they can better present chemistry in the classroom, foster the scientific curiosity of our nation's youth and encourage future generations to pursue scientific careers.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] As of 2009, Clifford and Kathryn Hach donated $33 million to ACS, to continue the work of the Hach Scientific Foundation in supporting high school chemistry teaching.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Society sponsors the United States National Chemistry Olympiad (USNCO), a contest used to select the four-member team that represents the United States at the International Chemistry Olympiad (IChO).
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS Division of Chemical Education provides standardized tests for various subfields of chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The two most commonly used tests are the undergraduate-level tests for general and organic chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Each of these tests consists of 70 multiple-choice questions, and gives students 110 minutes to complete the exam.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS also approves certified undergraduate programs in chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] A student who completes the required laboratory and course work—sometimes in excess of what a particular college may require for its Bachelor's degree—is considered by the Society to be well trained for professional work.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS coordinates two annual public awareness campaigns, National Chemistry Week and Chemists Celebrate Earth Week, as part of its educational outreach.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Since 1978 and 2003 respectively, the campaigns have been celebrated with a yearly theme, such as "Chemistry Colors Our World" (2015) and "Energy: Now and Forever!" (2013).
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The GCI was founded in 1997 as an independent non-profit organization, by chemists Joe Breen and Dennis Hjeresen in cooperation with the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Petroleum Research Fund (PRF) is an endowment fund administered by the ACS that supports advanced education and fundamental research in the petroleum and fossil fuel fields at non-profit institutions.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Several categories of grants are offered for various career levels and institutions.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The fund awarded more than $25 million in grants in 2007.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The PRF traces its origins to the acquisition of the Universal Oil Products laboratory by a consortium of oil companies in 1931.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The companies established a trust fund, The Petroleum Research Fund, in 1944 to prevent antitrust litigation tied to their UOP assets.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS was named the beneficiary of the trust.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The first grants from the PRF were awarded in 1954.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 2000, the trust was transferred to the ACS.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS established The American Chemical Society Petroleum Research Fund and the previous trust was dissolved.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The PRF trust was valued at $144.7 million in December 2014.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS International Activities is the birthplace of the ACS International Center, an online resource for scientists and engineers looking to study abroad or explore an international career or internship.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The site houses information on hundreds of scholarships and grants related to all levels of experience to promote scientific mobility of researchers and practitioners in STEM fields.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Society grants membership to undergraduates as student members provided they can pay the $25 yearly dues.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Any university may start its own ACS Student Chapter and receive benefits of undergraduate participation in regional conferences and discounts on ACS publications.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The American Chemical Society administers 64 national awards, medals and prizes based on scientific contributions at various career levels that promote achievement across the chemical sciences.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS national awards program began in 1922 with the establishment of the Priestley Medal, the highest award offered by the ACS, which is given for distinguished services to chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Additional awards are offered by divisions, local sections and other bodies of ACS.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Nichols Medal Award was the first ACS award to honor outstanding researchers in the field of chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] It was established in 1903 by the ACS New York Section and is named for William H.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Nichols, an American chemist and businessman and one of the original founders of ACS.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Of the over 100 Nichols Medalists, 16 have subsequently been awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Willard Gibbs Award, granted by the ACS Chicago Section, was established in 1910 in honor of Josiah Willard Gibbs, the Yale University professor who formulated the phase rule.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Georgia Local Section of ACS has awarded the Herty Medal since 1933 recognizing outstanding chemists who have significantly contributed to their chosen fields.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] All chemists in academic, government, or industrial laboratories who have been residing in the southeastern United States for at least 10 years are eligible.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The New York Section of ACS also gives Leadership Awards.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The Leadership Awards are the highest honors given by the Chemical Marketing and Economic Group of ACS NY since December 6, 2012.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] They are presented to leaders of industry, investments, and other sectors, for their contributions to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) initiatives.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Roy Vagelos (Regeneron, Merck), Thomas M.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Connelly (DuPont) and Juan Pablo del Valle (Mexichem).
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS also administers regional awards presented annually at regional meetings.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Ann Nalley Regional Award for Volunteer Service to the American Chemical Society, Regional Awards for Excellence in High School Teaching, and the Stanley C.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] Israel Regional Award for Advancing Diversity in the Chemical Sciences.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] ACS Publications is the publishing division of the ACS.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] It is a nonprofit academic publisher of scientific journals covering various fields of chemistry and related sciences.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In addition to academic journals, ACS Publications also publishes *Chemical & Engineering News*, a weekly trade magazine covering news in the chemical profession, *inChemistry*, a magazine for undergraduate students, and *ChemMatters*, a magazine for high school students and teachers.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] However it has recently launched new open access journals and provided authors with open access publishing options.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 2006, Congress debated legislation that would have instructed the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to require all investigators it funded to submit copies of final, peer-reviewed journal articles to PubMed Central, a free-access digital repository it operates, within 12 months of publication.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] At the time the American Association of Publishers (of which ACS is a member) hired a public relations firm to counter the open access movement.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In spite of publishers' opposition, the PubMed Central legislation was passed in December 2007 and became effective in 2008.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] As the open access issue has continued to evolve, so too has the ACS's position.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS has also introduced several open access publishing options for its journals, including providing authors the option to pay an upfront fee to enable free online access to their articles.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 2015, the ACS launched the first fully open access journal in the society's history, *ACS Central Science*.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS states that the journal offers the same peer-review standards as its subscription journals, but without publishing charges to either authors or readers.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] A second open access title, *ACS Omega*, an interdisciplinary mega journal, launched in 2016.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 2005, the ACS was criticized for opposing the creation of PubChem, which is an open access chemical database developed by the NIH's National Center for Biotechnology Information.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS raised concerns that the publicly supported PubChem database would duplicate and unfairly compete with their existing fee-based Chemical Abstracts Service and argued that the database should only present data created by the Molecular Libraries Screening Center initiative of the NIH.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS lobbied members of the United States Congress to rein in PubChem and hired outside lobbying firms to try to persuade congressional members, the NIH, and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) against establishing a publicly funded database.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS was unsuccessful, and as of 2012 PubChem is the world's largest free chemical database.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS is also the only provider of a major scientific publication database (SciFinder) that imposes a restriction on the number of records that can be exported.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] None of the competing products, such as Web of Science (owned by Clarivate), Scopus (owned by Elsevier) and The Lens (owned by Cambia) have similar restrictions.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS has been involved in numerous lawsuits regarding access to its databases, trademark rights, and copyrighted material.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In many of these cases, the ACS lost or ended up with an unenforceable judgement.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS was also found guilty in several lawsuits brought against the Society by its employees.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] In 2004, a group of ACS members criticized the compensation of former executive director and chief executive officer John Crum, whose total salary, expenses, and bonuses for 2002 was reported to be $767,834.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] The ACS defended the figure, saying that it was in line with that of comparable organizations, including for-profit publishers.
[src:compound-interest-website/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, two employees were reported to have a total compensation exceeding $900,000, while 694 had a compensation exceeding $100,000.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Published eight times per year, *Forbes* features articles on finance, industry, investing, and marketing topics.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] It also reports on related subjects such as technology, communications, science, politics, and law.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] It has an international edition in Asia as well as editions produced under license in 27 countries and regions worldwide.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Since 2010, the Forbes.com website has become increasingly reliant on freelance contributor network writers who have limited editorial oversight from the publication, the quality of which has been criticised and described as enabling "pay-to-play journalism".
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes, a financial columnist for the Hearst papers, and his partner Walter Drey, the general manager of the *Magazine of Wall Street*, founded *Forbes* magazine on September 15, 1917.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes provided the money and the name and Drey provided the publishing expertise.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The original name of the magazine was *Forbes: Devoted to Doers and Doings*.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes became editor-in-chief, a post he held until his death in 1954.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes was assisted in his later years by his two eldest sons, Bruce Charles Forbes (1916–1964) and Malcolm Forbes (1919–1990).
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Bruce Forbes took over after his father's death, and his strengths lay in streamlining operations and developing marketing.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] During his tenure, from 1954 to 1964, the magazine's circulation nearly doubled.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] On Bruce's death, his brother Malcolm Forbes became president and chief executive officer of Forbes, and editor-in-chief of *Forbes* magazine.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Between 1961 and 1999 the magazine was edited by James Michaels.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In 1993, under Michaels, *Forbes* was a finalist for the National Magazine Award.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In 2006, an investment group Elevation Partners that includes rock star Bono bought a minority interest in the company with a reorganization, through a new company, Forbes Media LLC, in which Forbes Magazine and Forbes.com, along with other media properties, is now a part.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] A 2009 *New York Times* report said: "40 percent of the enterprise was sold... for a reported $300 million, setting the value of the enterprise at $750 million." Three years later, Mark M.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Edmiston of AdMedia Partners observed, "It's probably not worth half of that now." It was later revealed that the price had been US$264 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In 2021, Forbes Media reported a return to profit, with revenue increasing by 34 percent to $165 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Much of the revenue growth was attributed to Forbes' consumer business, which was up 83 percent year-over-year.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] CEO Mike Federle says that Forbes is built on an audience and business scale with 150 million consumers.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In January 2010, *Forbes* reached an agreement to sell its headquarters building on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan to New York University; terms of the deal were not publicly reported, but Forbes was to continue to occupy the space under a five-year sale-leaseback arrangement.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The company's headquarters moved to the Newport section of downtown Jersey City, New Jersey, in 2014.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In November 2013, Forbes Media, which publishes *Forbes* magazine, was put up for sale.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] This was encouraged by minority shareholders Elevation Partners.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Sale documents prepared by Deutsche Bank revealed that the publisher's 2012 earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization was US$15 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] *Forbes* reportedly sought a price of US$400 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In July 2014, the Forbes family bought out Elevation and then Hong Kong-based investment group Integrated Whale Media Investments purchased a 51 percent majority of the company.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] On August 26, 2021, Forbes announced plans to go public via a merger with a special-purpose acquisition company called Magnum Opus Acquisition, and to trade on the New York Stock Exchange as FRBS.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In February 2022, it was announced that Cryptocurrency exchange Binance would acquire a $200 million stake in Forbes as a result of the SPAC flotation.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In June 2022, the company terminated its SPAC merger citing unfavorable market conditions.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In August 2022, the company announced that it was exploring a sale of its business.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In May 2023, it was announced that billionaire Austin Russell, founder of Luminar Technologies, agreed to acquire an 82 percent stake in a deal valuing the company at $800 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] His majority ownership was to include the remaining portion of the company owned by the Forbes family which was not previously sold to Integrated Whale Media.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The transaction attracted scrutiny by the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Russell denied reports that Russian businessman Magomed Musaev was involved in the transaction.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In November 2023, the deal collapsed, as Russell was unable to put together the necessary funds.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Chairman / Editor-in-chief Steve Forbes and his magazine's writers offer investment advice on the weekly Fox TV show *Forbes on Fox* and on *Forbes on Radio*.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Other company groups include Forbes Conference Group, Forbes Investment Advisory Group and Forbes Custom Media.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The company formerly published *American Legacy* magazine as a joint venture, although that magazine separated from Forbes on May 14, 2007.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The company also formerly published *American Heritage* and *Invention & Technology* magazines.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] After failing to find a buyer, Forbes suspended publication of these two magazines as of May 17, 2007.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Both magazines were purchased by the American Heritage Publishing Company and resumed publication as of the spring of 2008.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes has published the *Forbes Travel Guide* since 2009.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In 2013, Forbes licensed its brand to Ashford University, and assisted with the launch of the Forbes School of Business & Technology.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] CEO Mike Federle justified the licensing in 2018, stating that "Our licensing business is almost a pure-profit business, because it's an annual annuity." Forbes would launch limited promotions for the school in limited issues.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes has never formally endorsed the school.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] On January 6, 2014, *Forbes* magazine announced that, in partnership with app creator Maz, it was launching a social networking app called "Stream".
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Stream allows Forbes readers to save and share visual content with other readers and discover content from *Forbes* magazine and Forbes.com within the app.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] David Churbuck founded *Forbes*'s web site in 1996.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The site uncovered Stephen Glass's journalistic fraud in *The New Republic* in 1998, an article that drew attention to internet journalism.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] At the peak of media coverage of alleged Toyota sudden unintended acceleration in 2010, it exposed the California "runaway Prius" as a hoax, as well as running five other articles by Michael Fumento challenging the entire media premise of Toyota's cars gone bad.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The website (like the magazine) publishes lists focusing on billionaires and their possessions, especially real estate.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes.com is part of Forbes Digital, a division of Forbes Media LLC.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes's holdings include a portion of RealClearPolitics.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Together these sites reach more than 27 million unique visitors each month.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes.com employs the slogan "Home Page for the World's Business Leaders" and claimed, in 2006, to be the world's most widely visited business web site.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The 2009 *Times* report said that, while "one of the top five financial sites by traffic [throwing] off an estimated $70 million to $80 million a year in revenue, [it] never yielded the hoped-for public offering".
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes.com uses a contributor network in which a wide network of freelancers ("contributors") writes and publishes articles directly on the website.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Contributors are paid based on traffic to their respective Forbes.com pages; the site has received contributions from over 2,500 individuals, and some contributors have earned over US$100,000, according to the company.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] The contributor system has been criticized for enabling "pay-to-play journalism" and the repackaging of public relations material as news.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] *Forbes* currently allows advertisers to publish blog posts on its website alongside regular editorial content through a program called BrandVoice, which accounts for more than 10 percent of its digital revenue.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In July 2018, Forbes deleted an article by a contributor who argued that libraries should be closed and that Amazon should open bookstores in their place.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] As of 2019, the company published 100 articles each day, produced by 3,000 outside contributors who were paid little or nothing.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] This business model, in place since 2010, "changed their reputation from being a respectable business publication to a content farm", according to Damon Kiesow, the Knight Chair in digital editing and producing at the University of Missouri School of Journalism.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Similarly, Harvard University's Nieman Lab deemed Forbes "a platform for scams, grift, and bad journalism" as of 2022.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In 2017, the website blocked internet users using ad blocking software from accessing articles, requiring that the website be put on the ad blocking software's whitelist before access was granted.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes argued that this is done because customers using ad blocking software do not contribute to the site's revenue.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Malware attacks have been noted to occur from the Forbes site.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] Forbes won the 2020 Webby People's Voice Award for Business Blog/Website.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In November 2019, Forbes launched a streaming platform Forbes8, highlighting notable entrepreneurs and sharing business tips.
[src:compound-interest-website/forbes] In 2020, the network announced the release of several documentary series including *Forbes Rap Mentors*, *Driven Against the Odds*, *Indie Nation* and *Titans on the Rocks*.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:compound-interest-website/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Articles are written by academics and researchers under a Creative Commons licence, allowing reuse without modification.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Copyright terms for images are generally listed in the image caption and attribution.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Its model has been described as explanatory journalism.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Except in "exceptional circumstances", it only publishes articles by "academics employed by, or otherwise formally connected to, accredited institutions, including universities and accredited research bodies".
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The website was launched in Australia in March 2011.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The network has since expanded globally with a variety of local editions originating from around the world.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In September 2019, *The Conversation* reported a monthly online audience of 10.7 million users, and a combined reach of 40 million people when including republication.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The site employed more than 150 full-time staff as of 2020.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Each regional or national edition of *The Conversation* is an independent nonprofit or charity funded by various sources such as partnered universities and university systems, governments and other grant awarding bodies, corporate partners, and reader donations.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Jaspan first discussed the concept of *The Conversation* in 2009 with Glyn Davis, vice chancellor at the University of Melbourne.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] This vision became the blueprint for *The Conversation*.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Jaspan and Rejtman were provided support by Melbourne University in mid-2009, which allowed time to incubate the business model.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] By February 2010, they had developed their model, branding, and business identity that they launched to potential support partners through an Information Memorandum in February 2010.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The founders secured $10m in funding from four universities (Melbourne, Monash, Australian National University, University of Western Australia), CSIRO, the Government of Victoria, the Government of Australia and the Commonwealth Bank.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In March 2017, Andrew Jaspan resigned as executive director and editor, six months after being placed on enforced leave after complaints from senior staff in Melbourne about his management style and the group's global direction.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Management of the UK, U.S., and Africa offices also wrote a letter of no confidence to the Conversation Media Group asking that Jaspan not have an active role in the future.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Articles are written by academic researchers in their respective areas of expertise.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] They either pitch topics or are specifically commissioned to write on a topic in which they are a subject-matter expert, including for articles about current events.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] *The Conversation*'s core staff then edits these articles, ensuring a balance between reader accessibility and academic rigour.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Editors who work for the site frequently have past experience working for traditional news outlets.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The original authors then review the edited version.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Topics include politics, society, health, science, and the environment.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Authors are required to disclose conflicts of interest.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] All articles are published under a Creative Commons Attribution/No derivatives licence.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The site often publishes fact-checks produced by academics from major universities, then blind peer reviewed by another academic who comments on the accuracy of the fact check.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In 2016, the fact-check unit of *The Conversation* became accredited by the International Fact-Checking Network, an alliance of fact-checkers hosted at the Poynter Institute in the U.S.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The assessment criteria require non-partisanship, fairness, transparency of funding, sources, and methods, as well as a commitment to open and honest corrections.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Each edition of *The Conversation* has a unique content set, editor-in-chief, and board of advisors.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] From its first Melbourne-headquartered Australian edition, *The Conversation* has expanded to a global network of eight editions, operating in multiple languages.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] This has included expansions into the United Kingdom in 2013, United States in 2014, Africa and France in 2015, Canada, Indonesia, and New Zealand in 2017,.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Spain in 2018, Europe and Brasil in 2024.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The website also has an international staff.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] As of 2018, 36% of its readership was in Australia, 29% was in the United States, 7% in the United Kingdom, 4% in Canada, and 24% elsewhere.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Across the whole network, stories commissioned by *The Conversation* are now republished in 90 countries, in 23 languages, and read more than 40m times a month.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] As of 2021, most of the authors who published content in *The Conversation* Africa were affiliated with South African universities, and the website content initially focused on South Africa.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation provided $3m funding.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The idea to launch the Indonesian edition emerged after a 2015 meeting between Sangkot Marzuki (then Chair of AIPI) and The Conversation's founder, Andrew Jaspan.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The Conversation Indonesia Foundation was formally established on 4 September 2017, and the Indonesian edition went live on 6 September 2017 under Executive Editor Prodita Kusuma Sabarini.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The foundation's founders included press figure Aristides Katoppo, conservation biologist Jatna Supriatna, and molecular biologist Sangkot Marzuki, with RTS Masli providing the registered domicile.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] During its incubation phase, AIPI served as the host partner.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Over a two-year trial period, The Conversation Indonesia received grant support from the Myer Foundation, the Open Society Foundation, and the Embassy of France in Jakarta; the law firm Soemadipradja & Taher provided pro bono assistance.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Entering 2019, support continued from the Ford Foundation, the David and Lucile Packard Foundation, the Knowledge Sector Initiative program, and the Tifa Foundation—enabling newsroom expansion and the creation of new divisions (Finance & Management and Business Development & Partnership).
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] As part of the global Conversation network, the Indonesian edition publishes research-based analysis by academics and researchers under Creative Commons (with no paywall), allowing content to be freely read and republished by other media with proper attribution and installation of a countercode.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The newsroom also runs science-communication training as well as the Science Leadership Collaborative program for early-career researchers.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In recent years, the Packard Foundation has recorded multi-year grants to The Conversation Indonesia Foundation to support core operations, strengthen coverage of environmental and ocean issues, and develop new partnerships with universities and research institutions across Indonesia.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The Canadian edition of *The Conversation* was co-founded on 26 June 2017 by Alfred Hermida and Mary Lynn Young, associate professors in the field of journalism at the University of British Columbia.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Launch funding was partly provided in the form of a $200,000 grant from the Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The project was joined by Universities Canada as a strategic sponsor, and it partnered with a number of Canadian universities such as the University of Toronto.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The founding editor of The Conversation Canada is Scott White, the former editor-in-chief of The Canadian Press.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] A French-language Canadian edition, *La Conversation Canada*, launched in 2018.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] A French edition of the website launched in September 2015.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Didier Pourquery was the editor of the French edition at launch.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] It launched with Fabrice Rousselot as its publication director.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] It received initial backing from French academic institutions, including the University of Lorraine, France's Conference of University Presidents, Paris Sciences et Lettres University, and the Institut Universitaire de France.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Andrew Jaspan secured seed funding to develop the case to launch *The Conversation* into the UK in 2012.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] It launched in the UK on 16 May 2013 with Stephen Khan as editor, Jonathan Hyams as chief executive, and Max Landry as chief operating officer, alongside co-founder, Andrew Jaspan.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] It had 13 founder members, including City, University of London.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] City's president, professor Sir Paul Curran chaired its board of trustees.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] By February 2014, the site had attained additional funding from academic research institutions including Research Councils UK and SAGE Publishing.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] They then hired six additional editors and expanded the UK edition's topical coverage.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] By August 2014, the UK branch published articles written by approximately 3,000 academics.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Membership grew to more than 80 universities in the UK and Europe, including Cambridge, Oxford, and Trinity College Dublin.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] By 2019, it had published 24,000 articles written by 14,000 academics.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In April 2018, it appointed former BBC and AP executive Chris Waiting as its new CEO.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] *The Conversation* UK is 90 per cent funded by partnered universities, with other funding from the Higher Education Funding Council for England and the Wellcome Trust.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In 2019, the site became a member of the Independent Monitor for the Press, an independent press regulator.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Andrew Jaspan was invited in 2012 to bring *The Conversation* to the United States.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Thomas Fiedler, then dean of the School of Communications at Boston University, offered to host *The Conversation* U.S. and provide space for the first newsroom.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] With a university base established, he was able to raise the $2.3M launch funding.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The U.S. edition of *The Conversation* was first published on 21 October 2014, initially led by Jaspan as U.S.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] CEO, Margaret Drain as editor, and Bruce Wilson leading development and university relations.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The U.S. pilot was supported by the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, Alfred P.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Sloan Foundation, Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, the William and Flora Hewlett Foundation, and four other foundations.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Maria Balinska became editor in 2015, before she moved to the US-UK Fulbright Commission.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] She was succeeded by Beth Daley, who became editor and general manager in 2019.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] The U.S. edition of *The Conversation* was originally based at Boston University, and that was its first partnered university.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] It later opened offices in Atlanta and New York.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Other partnered institutions include Harvard University and MIT.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In January 2024, the US site launched a local-news focused outlet that opened in four markets: Detroit, South Florida, Colorado and Philadelphia.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] *The Conversation* Local, funded by the Knight Foundation, worked with 150 local outlets in its first year.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] Articles originally published in *The Conversation* have received regular republication from major news outlets.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] These have included *The New York Times*, *The Guardian*, *The Washington Post*, and CNN.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] As of 2015, approximately 80 percent of the site readership were of a non-academic background.
[src:compound-interest-website/the-conversation-website] In 2024, *Imagine Newsletter*, which covers climate change, won the Publisher Newsletter Awards for excellence in the category of science and technology.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] A European edition, *Time Europe*, is published in London and also covers the Middle East, Africa, and, Latin America.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] An Asian edition, *Time Asia*, is based in Hong Kong.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The South Pacific edition, which covers Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific Islands, is based in Sydney.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] *Time France* began publication in 2025.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Since 2018, *Time* has been owned by Salesforce founder Marc Benioff, who acquired it from Meredith Corporation.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Benioff currently publishes the magazine through the company Time USA, LLC.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Following Hadden's death in 1929, Luce became the dominant man at *Time* and a significant figure in the history of 20th-century media.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] According to *Time Inc.: The Intimate History of a Publishing Enterprise 1923–1941* by Robert Elson, "Roy Edward Larsen ... was to play a role second only to Luce's in the development of Time Inc".
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Around that time, they were raising $100,000 from wealthy Yale University alumni, including Henry P.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Morgan & Co., publicity man Martin Egan and J.P.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Henry Luce and Briton Hadden hired Larsen in 1922.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Larsen was a Harvard University graduate, and Luce and Hadden were Yale graduates.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] After Hadden died in 1929, Larsen purchased 550 shares of Time Inc., using money he obtained from selling RKO stock he had inherited from his father, who was the head of the Benjamin Franklin Keith theater chain in New England.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] After Briton Hadden's death, the largest Time, Inc. stockholder was Henry Luce, who ruled the media conglomerate in an autocratic fashion.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] "At his right hand was Larsen", Time Inc.'s second-largest stockholder, according to *Time Inc.: The Intimate History of a Publishing Enterprise 1923–1941*.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 1929, Roy Larsen was named a Time Inc. director and vice president.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Morgan retained a certain control through two directorates and a share of stocks, both over *Time* and *Fortune*.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Other shareholders were Brown Brothers Harriman & Co., and the New York Trust Company (Standard Oil).
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] After *Time* began publishing weekly in March 1923, Roy Larsen increased its circulation by using U.S. radio and movie theaters worldwide.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] It often promoted both *Time* magazine and U.S. political and corporate interests.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] According to *The March of Time*, in 1924 Larsen brought *Time* into the infant radio business by broadcasting a 15-minute quiz show called *Pop Question*, which survived until 1925.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 1928, Larsen "undertook the weekly broadcast of a 10-minute programme series of brief news summaries, drawn from current issues of *Time* magazine ... which was originally broadcast over 33 stations throughout the United States".
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In March 1931, Larsen introduced a 30-minute radio program, *The March of Time*, to be broadcast over CBS.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Each week, the program presented a dramatization of the week's news for its listeners.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Thus *Time* magazine was brought "to the attention of millions previously unaware of its existence", according to *Time Inc.: The Intimate History of a Publishing Enterprise 1923–1941*, leading to increased circulation during the 1930s.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Between 1931 and 1937, Larsen's *The March of Time* radio program was broadcast over CBS radio.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Between 1937 and 1945, it was broadcast over NBC radio – except between 1939 and 1941, when it was not aired.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] *People* magazine was based on *Time*'s "People" page.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The Larsen family's Time Inc. stock was worth around $80 million during the 1960s.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Roy Larsen was both a Time Inc. director and the chairman of its executive committee, later serving as Time Inc.'s board's vice chairman until the middle of 1979.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] On September 10, 1979, *The New York Times* wrote, "Mr.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 1987, Jason McManus succeeded Henry Grunwald as editor-in-chief, and oversaw the transition before Norman Pearlstine succeeded him in 1995.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 1989, when Time, Inc. and Warner Communications merged, *Time* became part of Time Warner, along with Warner Bros.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2000, *Time* became part of AOL Time Warner, which reverted to the name Time Warner in 2003.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2007, *Time* moved from a Monday subscription/newsstand delivery to a schedule where the magazine goes on sale Fridays and is delivered to subscribers on Saturday.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The magazine was published on Fridays when it began in 1923.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In early 2007, the year's first issue was delayed roughly a week due to "editorial changes", including the layoff of 49 employees.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2009, Time announced it was introducing *Mine*, a personalized print magazine mixing content from various Time Warner publications based on the reader's preferences.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The new magazine was met with a poor reception, with criticism that its focus needed to be more broad to be truly personal.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The magazine has an online archive with the unformatted text for every article published.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The articles were indexed and converted from scanned images using optical character recognition technology.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The minor errors in the text are remnants of the conversion to the digital format.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In January 2013, Time Inc. announced that it would cut nearly 500 jobs – roughly 6% of its 8,000 staff worldwide.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Although *Time* magazine has maintained high sales, its ad pages have declined significantly.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Also in January 2013, Time Inc. named Martha Nelson as the first female editor-in-chief of its magazine division.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In September 2013, Nancy Gibbs was named as the first female managing editor of *Time* magazine.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In November 2017, Meredith Corporation announced its acquisition of Time, Inc., backed by Koch Equity Development.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2017, editor and journalist Catherine Mayer, who also founded the Women's Equality Party in the UK, sued *Time* through attorney Ann Olivarius for sex and age discrimination.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In March 2018, only six weeks after the closure of the sale, Meredith announced that it would explore the sale of *Time* and sister magazines *Fortune*, *Money* and *Sports Illustrated*, since they did not align with the company's lifestyle brands.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In October 2018, Meredith Corporation sold *Time* to Marc Benioff and his wife Lynne for $190 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Benioff is the chairman and co-CEO of Salesforce.com.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] *Time* is to remain separate from that company, with Benioff not involved in the magazine's daily operations.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Forbes COO Jessica Sibley was appointed CEO of Time in November 2022.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Stating that she intended for the company to be "cash flow positive" by 2025, Sibley oversaw a number of immediate changes.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] According to Sibley, her first focus was pivoting the company away from business-to-consumer revenues to business-to-business revenues, resulting in *Time* dropping its online paywall in June 2023.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] She also hired new executives, including new chief revenue officers, a new editor-in-chief, and a new chief strategy officer.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] She oversaw layoffs at *Time* in 2024, calling them necessary to improve the company's financial position.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The layoffs were criticized by The NewsGuild of New York and the Time Union.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The layoffs were part of a broader strategy to focus on covering leadership (*Time*'s most commercially successful area) and to "provide journalism that serves these present and future leaders", including leaders in climate, AI, and health coverage.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] As of 2025, *Time*'s circulation has been steadily declining.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] During the second half of 2009, the magazine had a 34.9% decline in newsstand sales.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] During the first half of 2010, there was another decline of 30%.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2012, *Time* had a circulation of 3.3 million, making it the 11th-most circulated magazine in the United States, and the second-most circulated weekly behind *People*.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In October 2017, *Time* circulation dropped to two million.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In early 2023 Time had 1.3 million print subscribers and 250,000 digital subscribers.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Combined print and digital circulation was 1 million for the six months to 31 December 2024, down 7.1% year-on-year.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Since its first issue, *Time* has had a "Milestones" section about significant events in the lives of famous people, including births, marriages, divorces, and deaths.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Until 1967, entries in Milestones were short and formulaic.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Until the mid-1970s, *Time* had a weekly "Listings" section with capsule summaries or reviews of current significant films, plays, musicals, television programs, and literary bestsellers similar to *The New Yorker*'s "Current Events" section.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Former president Richard Nixon has been among the most frequently featured on the cover of *Time*, having appeared 55 times from August 25, 1952, to May 2, 1994.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In October 2020, the magazine replaced its logo with the word "Vote", explaining that "Few events will shape the world to come more than the result of the upcoming US presidential election".
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2007, *Time* redesigned the magazine to update and modernize the format.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Among other changes, the magazine reduced the red cover border to promote featured stories, enlarged column titles, reduced the number of featured stories, increased white space around articles, and accompanied opinion pieces with photographs of the writers.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The changes were met with both criticism and praise.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2006, Person of the Year was "You", and was met with split reviews.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Some thought the concept was creative; others wanted an actual person of the year.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Editors Pepper and Timmer reflected that, if it had been a mistake, "we're only going to make it once".
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2017, *Time* named the "Silence Breakers", people who came forward with personal stories of sexual harassment, as Person of the Year.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In recent years, *Time* has assembled an annual list of the 100 most influential people of the year.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Originally, they had made a list of the 100 most influential people of the 20th century.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] These issues usually have the front cover filled with pictures of people from the list and devote a substantial amount of space within the magazine to the 100 articles about each person on the list.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In some cases, over 100 people have been included, as when two people have made the list together, sharing one spot.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The magazine also compiled "All-Time 100 best novels" and "All-Time 100 Movies" lists in 2005, "The 100 Best TV Shows of All-Time" in 2007, and "All-Time 100 Fashion Icons" in 2012.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In February 2016, *Time* mistakenly included the male author Evelyn Waugh on its "100 Most Read Female Writers in College Classes" list (he was 97th on the list).
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The error created much media attention and concerns about the level of basic education among the magazine's staff.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In a BBC interview with Justin Webb, Professor Valentine Cunningham of Corpus Christi College, Oxford, described the mistake as "a piece of profound ignorance on the part of *Time* magazine".
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] During its history, on seven occasions, *Time* has released a special issue with a cover showing an X scrawled over the face of a man, a year, or a national symbol.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The first *Time* magazine with an X cover was released on May 7, 1945, showing a red X over Adolf Hitler's face which was published the week following his death.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The second X cover was released on August 20, 1945, with a black X (to date, the magazine's only such use of a black X) covering the flag of Japan, representing the recent surrender of Japan and which signaled the end of World War II.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Fifty-eight years later, on April 21, 2003, *Time* released another issue with a red X over Saddam Hussein's face, two weeks after the start of the Invasion of Iraq.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] A third red X issue was on June 19, 2006, after Abu Musab al-Zarqawi was killed.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] A fourth red X cover issue was published on May 20, 2011, after the death of Osama bin Laden.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] A fifth red X cover issue on December 14, 2020, had a red X scrawled over the pandemic-hit year 2020 and the declaration "the worst year ever".
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] As of 2024, the most recent and seventh X cover issue of *Time*, that of Nov.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] 11, 2024, features a red X over the face of Yahya Sinwar following his killing by the Israel Defense Forces.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] From 1942 until 1979, *Time* had a Canadian edition that included an insert of five pages of locally produced content and occasional Canadian covers.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Following changes in the tax status of Canadian editions of American magazines, *Time* closed Canadian bureaus, except for Ottawa, and published identical content to the US edition but with Canadian advertising.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In December 2008, *Time* discontinued publishing a Canadian edition.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In December 2025, *Time France* became the first ever foreign licensed edition of *Time* magazine.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] It is published quarterly by 360BusinessMedia and 100,000 copies are printed of each issue.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The magazine is distributed across France, Belgium, Luxembourg, Switzerland and Monaco.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] The cover of the first issue featured American actress Angelina Jolie.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Time LightBox is a photography blog created and curated by the magazine's photo department that was launched in 2011.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] In 2011, *Life* picked LightBox for its Photo Blog Awards.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] TimePieces is a Web3 community NFT initiative from *Time*.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] It included works from over 40 artists from multiple disciplines.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Richard Stengel was the managing editor from May 2006 to October 2013, when he joined the U.S.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Nancy Gibbs was the managing editor from September 2013 until September 2017.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] She was succeeded by Edward Felsenthal, who had been *Time*'s digital editor.
[src:compound-interest-website/time-magazine] Writer William Saroyan (1908–1981) lists the complete *Time* editorial department in his 1940 play *Love's Old Sweet Song*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In its early years, it went through several owners and struggled financially and editorially.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1933, financier Eugene Meyer purchased it out of bankruptcy and revived its health and reputation; his successors Katharine and Phil Graham, Meyer's daughter and son-in-law, bought out several rival publications and continued this work.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post*'s 1971 printing of the Pentagon Papers helped spur opposition to the Vietnam War.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein led the investigation into the break-in at the Democratic National Committee, which developed into the Watergate scandal and the 1974 resignation of President Richard Nixon.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In October 2013, the Graham family sold the newspaper to Nash Holdings, a holding company owned by Jeff Bezos, for US$250 million.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The newspaper has won 76 Pulitzer Prizes, second only to *The New York Times*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] *Washington Post* journalists have received 18 Nieman Fellowships and 368 White House News Photographers Association awards.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Well-known for its political reporting in the U.S., it is one of the few American newspapers that still operate foreign bureaus, with international breaking news hubs in London and Seoul.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] As of 2021, the newspaper had 21 foreign bureaus: Baghdad, Beijing, Beirut, Berlin, Brussels, Cairo, Dakar, Hong Kong, Islamabad, Istanbul, Jerusalem, London, Mexico City, Moscow, Nairobi, New Delhi, Rio de Janeiro, Rome, Seoul, Tokyo, and Toronto.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The newspaper has local bureaus in Maryland (Annapolis, Montgomery County, Prince George's County, and Southern Maryland) and Virginia (Alexandria, Fairfax, Loudoun County, Richmond, and Prince William County).
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2009, the newspaper closed three U.S. regional bureaus—in Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York City—as part of an increased focus on Washington, D.C.–based political stories and local news.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] For many decades, the *Post* had its main office at 1150 15th Street NW.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] This real estate remained with Graham Holdings when the newspaper was sold to Jeff Bezos' Nash Holdings in 2013.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Graham Holdings sold 1150 15th Street, along with 1515 L Street, 1523 L Street, and land beneath 1100 15th Street, for $159 million in November 2013.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] *The Post* continued to lease space at 1150 L Street NW.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In May 2014, *The Post* leased the west tower of One Franklin Square, a high-rise building at 1301 K Street NW in Washington, D.C.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The newspaper was founded in 1877 by Stilson Hutchins (1838–1912); in 1880, it added a Sunday edition, becoming the city's first newspaper to publish seven days a week.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In April 1878, about four months into publication, *The Washington Post* purchased *The Washington Union*, a competing newspaper which was founded by John Lynch in late 1877.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Union* had only been in operation about six months at the time of the acquisition.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The combined newspaper was published from the Globe Building as *The Washington Post and Union* beginning on April 15, 1878, with a circulation of 13,000.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post and Union* name was used about two weeks until April 29, 1878, returning to the original masthead the following day.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1889, Hutchins sold the newspaper to Frank Hatton, a former Postmaster General, and Beriah Wilkins, a former Democratic congressman from Ohio.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] To promote the newspaper, the new owners requested the leader of the United States Marine Band, John Philip Sousa, to compose a march for the newspaper's essay contest awards ceremony.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] It became the standard music to accompany the two-step, a late 19th-century dance craze, and remains one of Sousa's best-known works.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1893, the newspaper moved to a building at 14th and E streets NW, where it would stay until 1950.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] This building combined all functions of the newspaper into one headquarters – newsroom, advertising, typesetting, and printing – that ran 24 hours per day.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1898, during the Spanish–American War, the *Post* printed Clifford K.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Berryman's classic illustration *Remember the Maine*, which became the battle-cry for American sailors during the War.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1902, Berryman published another famous cartoon in the *Post* – *Drawing the Line in Mississippi*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] This cartoon depicts President Theodore Roosevelt showing compassion for a small bear cub and inspired New York store owner Morris Michtom to create the teddy bear.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Wilkins acquired Hatton's share of the newspaper in 1894 at Hatton's death.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] After Wilkins died in 1903, his sons John and Robert ran the *Post* for two years before selling it in 1905 to John Roll McLean, owner of the *Cincinnati Enquirer*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] During the Wilson presidency, the *Post* was credited with the "most famous newspaper typo" in D.C. history according to *Reason* magazine; the *Post* intended to report that President Wilson had been "entertaining" his future-wife Mrs.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Galt, but instead wrote that he had been "entering" Mrs.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] When McLean died in 1916, he put the newspaper in a trust, having little faith that his playboy son Edward "Ned" McLean could manage it as part of his inheritance.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Ned went to court and broke the trust, but, under his management, the newspaper slumped toward ruin.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] He bled the paper for his lavish lifestyle and used it to promote political agendas.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] During the Red Summer of 1919 the Post supported the white mobs and even ran a front-page story which advertised the location at which white servicemen were planning to meet to carry out attacks on black Washingtonians.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1929, financier Eugene Meyer, who had run the War Finance Corp. since World War I, secretly made an offer of $5 million for the *Post,* but he was rebuffed by Ned McLean.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] On June 1, 1933, Meyer bought the paper at a bankruptcy auction for $825,000 three weeks after stepping down as Chairman of the Federal Reserve.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] He had bid anonymously, and was prepared to go up to $2 million, far higher than the other bidders.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] These included William Randolph Hearst, who had long hoped to shut down the ailing *Post* to benefit his own Washington newspaper presence.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post*'s health and reputation were restored under Meyer's ownership.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1946, he was succeeded as publisher by his son-in-law, Philip Graham.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Meyer eventually gained the last laugh over Hearst, who had owned the old *Washington Times* and the *Herald* before their 1939 merger that formed the *Times-Herald.* This was, in turn, bought by and merged into the *Post* in 1954.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The combined paper was officially named *The Washington Post and Times-Herald* until 1973, although the *Times-Herald* portion of the nameplate became less and less prominent over time.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The merger left the *Post* with two remaining local competitors, the *Washington Star* (*Evening Star*) and *The Washington Daily News*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] After Graham died in 1963, control of The Washington Post Company passed to his wife, Katharine Graham (1917–2001), who was also Eugene Meyer's daughter.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Few women had run prominent national newspapers in the United States, and Katharine Graham said that she was particularly anxious about assuming this role.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] She served as publisher from 1969 to 1979.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Graham took The Washington Post Company public on June 15, 1971, in the midst of the Pentagon Papers controversy.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] A total of 1,294,000 shares were offered to the public at $26 per share.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] By the end of Graham's tenure as CEO in 1991, the stock was worth $888 per share, not counting the effect of an intermediate 4:1 stock split.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Graham also oversaw the Post company's diversification purchase of the for-profit education and training company Kaplan, Inc. for $40 million in 1984.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Twenty years later, Kaplan had surpassed the *Post* newspaper as the company's leading contributor to income, and by 2010 Kaplan accounted for more than 60% of the entire company revenue stream.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Executive editor Ben Bradlee put the newspaper's reputation and resources behind reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein, who, in a long series of articles, chipped away at the story behind the 1972 burglary of Democratic National Committee offices in the Watergate complex in Washington.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post*'s dogged coverage of the story, the outcome of which ultimately played a major role in the resignation of President Richard Nixon, won the newspaper a Pulitzer Prize in 1973.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1972, the "Book World" section was introduced with Pulitzer Prize-winning critic William McPherson as its first editor.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] It featured Pulitzer Prize-winning critics such as Jonathan Yardley and Michael Dirda, the latter of whom established his career as a critic at the *Post*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] However, book reviews are still published in the Outlook section on Sundays and in the Style section the rest of the week, as well as online.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Graham, Katharine's son, succeeded her as a publisher in 1979.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1995, the domain name washingtonpost.com was purchased.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] That same year, a failed effort to create an online news repository called Digital Ink launched.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The following year, it was shut down, and the first website was launched in June 1996.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In August 2013, Jeff Bezos purchased *The Washington Post* and other local publications, websites, and real estate for US$250 million, transferring ownership to Nash Holdings LLC, Bezos's private investment company.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The paper's former parent company, which retained some other assets such as Kaplan and a group of TV stations, was renamed Graham Holdings shortly after the sale.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Nash Holdings, which includes the *Post*, is operated separately from technology company Amazon, which Bezos founded and where he is as of 2022 executive chairman and the largest single shareholder, with 12.7% of voting rights.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Bezos said he has a vision that recreates "the 'daily ritual' of reading the *Post* as a bundle, not merely a series of individual stories..." He has been described as a "hands-off owner", holding teleconference calls with executive editor Martin Baron every two weeks.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Bezos appointed Fred Ryan (founder and CEO of *Politico*) to serve as publisher and chief executive officer.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] This signaled Bezos' intent to shift the *Post* to a more digital focus with a national and global readership.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2015, the *Post* moved from the building it owned at 1150 15th Street to a leased space three blocks away at One Franklin Square on K Street.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Since 2014 the *Post* has launched an online personal finance section, a blog, and a podcast with a retro theme.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* won the 2020 Webby People's Voice Award for News & Politics in the Social and Web categories.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2017, the newspaper hired Jamal Khashoggi as a columnist.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2018, Khashoggi was murdered by Saudi agents in Istanbul.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2018, Monica Hesse was appointed the paper's first ever gender columnist.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] 17 days later, the Post published "Why can’t we hate men?", a #MeToo-inspired op-ed written by Suzanna Danuta Walters, the director of women’s studies at Northeastern University.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Some media outlets objected to it, including *The Atlantic*, the American Enterprise Institute, *The National Review*, *Quillette*, and the *Washington Post* itself.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Six months after Hesse's appointment, the Post published Amber Heard's op-ed, "I spoke up against sexual violence — and faced our culture’s wrath.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] That has to change." This article ultimately led to a lawsuit filed in 2019 by Johnny Depp against Amber Heard for defamation.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] After a 7-week jury trial, Heard was found liable for defaming Depp, who received $15 million in damages.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In October 2023, the *Post* announced it would cut 240 jobs across the organization by offering voluntary separation packages to employees.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In a staff-wide email announcing the job cuts, interim CEO Patty Stonesifer wrote, "Our prior projections for traffic, subscriptions and advertising growth for the past two years — and into 2024 — have been overly optimistic".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* has lost around 500,000 subscribers since the end of 2020 and was set to lose $100 million in 2023, according to *The New York Times*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] As part of the shift in tone, in 2023 the paper closed down the "KidsPost" column for children, the "Skywatch" astronomy column, and the "John Kelly's Washington" column about local history and sights, which had been running under different bylines since 1947.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In June 2024, Axios reported the *Post*faced significant internal turmoil and financial challenges.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Lewis quickly generated controversy with his leadership style and proposed restructuring plans.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The abrupt departure of executive editor Sally Buzbee and the appointment of two white men to top editorial positions sparked internal discontent, particularly given the lack of consideration for the Post's senior female editors.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Additionally, Lewis' proposed division for social media and service journalism was met with resistance from staff.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Staffers also became worried about Lewis' drinking and uninvolved role in the newsroom.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Lewis continued to grapple with declining revenue and readership, and sought strategies to regain subscribers lost since the Trump era.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Later that month, the paper ran a story allegedly exposing a connection between incoming editor Robert Winnett and John Ford, a man who "admitted to an extensive career using deception and illegal means to obtain confidential information." Winnett withdrew from the position shortly thereafter.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In January 2025, the *Post* announced it will layoff 4% of its staff, less than 100 people.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Newsroom employees will not be affected.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Also in January 2025, the Post scrapped the paper's "gender columnist" role and reassigned Hesse from the Style/Power section to the Opinions section after Post editors rejected an article she recently submitted.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] This change was confirmed by Hesse herself in an article she wrote in March 2025.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In June 2025, the Post announced the upcoming launch of *Ripple,* a section of the Post's website that will allow columnists and non-professional writers from various newspapers and blogs to write opinion pieces.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Non-professional writers will be allowed to use *Ember*, an AI tool created by the Post to help them write articles.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] On January 14, 2026, as part of the court case *United States v.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Aurelio Luis Perez-Lugones,* the FBI raided the apartment of a *Post* journalist, Hannah Natanson, and seized her phone, two laptops, and a smartwatch.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Investigators said to Natanson that the focus of the probe was not her but Aurelio Perez-Lugones, a system administrator with top-secret security clearance, under investigation for taking home classified intelligence reports.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The day after, the *Post*'s editorial board called the search an "aggressive attack on the press freedom of all journalists".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] On February 4, 2026, it was announced that around 300 *Post* employees would be laid off.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The paper's sports and books coverage are expected to be closed entirely, and its local news coverage will be substantially cut.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Additionally, their daily news "Post Reports" podcast, which ran for seven years, has been suspended.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Several foreign bureaus were closed, and at least one correspondent in Ukraine was laid off.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] According to *The New York Times*, in the week following these job cuts, more than 60,000 readers cancelled their digital subscriptions.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The layoffs were driven by a reported $100 million of losses in 2024, subscriber drops following the paper's refusal to endorse a presidential candidate in the 2024 US election, and falling search traffic from AI tools.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] On February 7, 2026, it was announced that Will Lewis, the paper's publisher, would step down and be replaced in the interim by Jeff D'Onofrio, who served as the company's chief financial officer.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The Washington Post Guild employees union welcomed the change in leadership, stating that Lewis will be remembered for "the attempted destruction of a great American journalism institution", and urged Bezos to "sell the paper to someone willing to invest in its future".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In February 2025, Bezos announced that the opinion section of the *Post* would publish only pieces that support "personal liberties and free markets".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] David Shipley, *The Post*'s opinion editor, resigned after failing to persuade Bezos to reconsider.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Within two days of the announcement, it was reported that more than 75,000 digital subscribers had canceled their subscriptions.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The following month, publisher Will Lewis killed a column by opinion columnist and editor Ruth Marcus criticizing the new direction.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Marcus resigned, ending her 40-year tenure with the newspaper.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] After the killing of Charlie Kirk in September 2025, the *Post* fired columnist and founding global opinion editor Karen Attiah, citing violations of its social media policy.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Attiah said she was punished for "speaking out against political violence, racial double standards, and America's apathy toward guns", arguing the US "accepts and worships" gun violence.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] *Politico* noted that only one post mentioned Kirk; it referred to his statement that Black women "do not have the brain processing power" to be taken seriously.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Attiah said her posts "made clear that not performing over-the-top grief for white men who espouse violence was not the same as endorsing violence against them", and described being pushed out after 11 years of service "for doing my job as a journalist" as a deeply "cruel 180".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] She was the last Black full-time writer at the opinion desk.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1933, financier Eugene Meyer bought the bankrupt *Post*, and assured the public that neither he nor the newspaper would be beholden to any political party.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] But as a leading Republican who had been appointed Chairman of the Federal Reserve by Herbert Hoover in 1930, his opposition to Roosevelt's New Deal colored the paper's editorials and news coverage, including editorializing news stories written by Meyer under a pseudonym.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] His wife Agnes Ernst Meyer was a journalist from the other end of the spectrum politically.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* ran many of her pieces including tributes to her personal friends John Dewey and Saul Alinsky.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1946, Meyer was appointed head of World Bank, and he named his son-in-law Phil Graham to succeed him as *Post* publisher.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The post-war years saw the developing friendship of Phil and Kay Graham with the Kennedys, the Bradlees and the rest of the "Georgetown Set", including many Harvard University alumni that would color the *Post's* political orientation.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Kay Graham's most memorable Georgetown soirée guest list included British diplomat and communist spy Donald Maclean.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* is credited with coining the term "McCarthyism" in a 1950 editorial cartoon by Herbert Block.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Depicting buckets of tar, it made fun of Sen.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Joseph McCarthy's "tarring" tactics, i.e., smear campaigns and character assassination against those targeted by his accusations.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] McCarthy was attempting to do for the Senate what the House Un-American Activities Committee had been doing for years—investigating Soviet espionage in America.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The HUAC made Richard Nixon nationally known for his role in the Hiss/Chambers case that exposed communist spying in the State Department.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The committee had evolved from the McCormack-Dickstein Committee of the 1930s.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Kennedy remained strong until they died in 1963.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Edgar Hoover reportedly told the new President Lyndon B.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Johnson, "I don't have much influence with the *Post* because I frankly don't read it.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Ben Bradlee became the editor-in-chief in 1968, and Kay Graham officially became the publisher in 1969, paving the way for the aggressive reporting of the *Pentagon Papers* and Watergate scandals.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* strengthened public opposition to the Vietnam War in 1971 when it published the *Pentagon Papers*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In the mid-1970s, some conservatives referred to the *Post* as "*Pravda* on the Potomac" because of its perceived left-wing bias in both reporting and editorials.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Since then, the appellation has been used by both liberal and conservative critics of the newspaper.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In the PBS documentary *Buying the War*, journalist Bill Moyers said in the year before the Iraq War there were 27 editorials supporting the Bush administration's desire to invade Iraq.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] National security correspondent Walter Pincus reported that he had been ordered to cease his reports that were critical of the administration.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] According to author and journalist Greg Mitchell: "By the *Post*'s own admission, in the months before the war, it ran more than 140 stories on its front page promoting the war, while contrary information got lost".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] On March 23, 2007, Chris Matthews said on his television program, "*The Washington Post* is not the liberal newspaper it was [...] I have been reading it for years and it is a neocon newspaper".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] It has regularly published a mixture of op-ed columnists, with some of them left-leaning (including E.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Dionne, Dana Milbank, Greg Sargent, and Eugene Robinson), and some of them right-leaning (including George Will, Marc Thiessen, Michael Gerson and Charles Krauthammer).
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Since 2011, the *Post* has been running a column called "The Fact Checker" that the *Post* describes as a "truth squad".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The Fact Checker received a $250,000 grant from Google News Initiative/YouTube to expand production of video fact checks.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In mid-September 2016, Matthew Ingram of *Forbes* joined Glenn Greenwald of *The Intercept*, and Trevor Timm of *The Guardian* in criticizing *The Washington Post* for "demanding that [former National Security Agency contractor Edward] Snowden ... stand trial on espionage charges".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] After Donald Trump was elected in 2016, the *Post* adopted the slogan "Democracy Dies in Darkness" for its masthead.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Communications Director of the *Post* Shani George said they choose this slogan because it "conveys who we are to the many millions of readers who have come to us for the first time over the last year".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] He also stated that the slogan was not added in response to Trump's actions.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In February 2025, Jeff Bezos announced that the paper's opinion pages would endorse "personal liberties and free markets" to the exclusion of other views.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] According to the NPR, the announcement suggested the *Post* was adopting a libertarian line.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In October 2025, columnist Marc Thiessen stated that the paper's opinion section was now conservative.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Robinson said that the paper has shifted from a centre-left economical stance to a hard-right one, opposing taxation of rich individuals, rent control, public transport, social housing and other social services.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] A significant number of articles in *The Washington Post* reportedly criticised labor unions and supported construction of new AI data centers.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In the vast majority of U.S. elections, for federal, state, and local office, the *Post* editorial board has endorsed Democratic candidates.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The paper's editorial board and endorsement decision-making are separate from newsroom operations.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Until 1976, the *Post* did not regularly make endorsements in presidential elections.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* editorial board endorsed Barack Obama in 2008 and 2012; Hillary Clinton in 2016; and Joe Biden in 2020.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2024, the *Post* controversially announced that it would no longer publish presidential endorsements.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] While the newspaper predominantly endorses Democrats in congressional, state, and local elections, it has occasionally endorsed Republican candidates.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] It endorsed Maryland Governor Robert Ehrlich's unsuccessful bid for a second term in 2006.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2006, it repeated its historic endorsements of every Republican incumbent for Congress in Northern Virginia.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* editorial board endorsed Virginia's Republican U.S.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Senator John Warner in his Senate reelection campaign in 1990, 1996 and 2002; the paper's most recent endorsement of a Maryland Republican for U.S.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Senate was in the 1980s, when the paper endorsed Senator Charlies "Mac" Mathias Jr.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] House of Representatives elections, moderate Republicans in Virginia and Maryland, including Wayne Gilchrest, Thomas M.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Davis, and Frank Wolf, have enjoyed the support of the *Post*; the *Post* also endorsed Republican Carol Schwartz in her campaign in Washington, D.C.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Eleven days before the 2024 presidential election, CEO and publisher William Lewis announced that the *Post* would not endorse a candidate for 2024.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] It was the first time since the 1988 presidential election that the paper did not endorse the Democratic candidate.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Lewis also said that the paper would not make endorsements in any future presidential election.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Editor-at-large Robert Kagan and columnist Michele Norris resigned in the wake of the decision, and editor David Maraniss said that the paper was "dying in darkness", a reference to the paper's current slogan.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] *Post* opinion columnists jointly authored an article calling the decision to not endorse a "terrible mistake", and it was condemned by the Washington Post Guild, a union unit representing *Post* employees.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] More than 250,000 people (about ten percent of the *Post*'s subscribers) cancelled their subscriptions, and three members of the editorial board left the board, though they remain with the *Post* in other positions.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Condemning the *Post*'s decision, several columnists, including Will Bunch, Jonathan Last, Dan Froomkin, Donna Ladd and Sewell Chan, described it as an example of what historian Timothy Snyder calls anticipatory obedience.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In September 1980, a Sunday feature story appeared on the front page of the *Post* titled "Jimmy's World" in which reporter Janet Cooke wrote a profile of the life of an eight-year-old heroin addict.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Although some within the *Post* doubted the story's veracity, the paper's editors defended it, and assistant managing editor Bob Woodward submitted the story to the Pulitzer Prize Board at Columbia University for consideration.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Cooke was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for Feature Writing on April 13, 1981.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The story was subsequently found to be a complete fabrication, and the Pulitzer was returned.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In July 2009, amid an intense debate over health care reform, *Politico* reported that a health-care lobbyist had received an "astonishing" offer of access to the *Post*'s "health-care reporting and editorial staff".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] *Post* publisher Katharine Weymouth had planned a series of exclusive dinner parties or "salons" at her private residence, to which she had invited prominent lobbyists, trade group members, politicians, and business people.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Participants were to be charged $25,000 to sponsor a single salon, and $250,000 for 11 sessions, which were closed to the public and to the non-*Post* press.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The idea drew swift criticism as an apparent ploy to allow insiders to purchase face time with *Post* staff.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Weymouth quickly canceled the salons, saying, "This should never have happened." White House counsel Gregory B.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Craig reminded officials that under federal ethics rules, they need advance approval for such events.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Dating back to 2011, *The Washington Post* began to include "China Watch" advertising supplements provided by *China Daily*, an English language newspaper owned by the Publicity Department of the Chinese Communist Party, on the print and online editions.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Although the header to the online "China Watch" section included the text "A Paid Supplement to The Washington Post", James Fallows of *The Atlantic* suggested that the notice was not clear enough for most readers to see.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Distributed to the *Post* and multiple newspapers around the world, the "China Watch" advertising supplements range from four to eight pages and appear at least monthly.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2020, a report by Freedom House, titled "Beijing's Global Megaphone", criticized the *Post* and other newspapers for distributing "China Watch".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In the same year, 35 Republican members of the U.S.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Department of Justice in February 2020 calling for an investigation of potential FARA violations by *China Daily*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2020, *The Post* suspended reporter Felicia Sonmez after she posted a series of tweets about the 2003 rape allegation against basketball star Kobe Bryant after Bryant's death.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] She was reinstated after over 200 *Post* journalists wrote an open letter criticizing the paper's decision.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In July 2021, Sonmez sued *The Post* and several of its top editors, alleging workplace discrimination; the suit was dismissed in March 2022, with the court determining that Sonmez had failed to make plausible claims.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In June 2022, Sonmez engaged in a Twitter feud with fellow *Post* staffers David Weigel, criticizing him over what he later described as "an offensive joke", and Jose A.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Del Real, who accused Sonmez of "engaging in repeated and targeted public harassment of a colleague".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Following the feud, the newspaper suspended Weigel for a month for violating the company's social media guidelines, and the newspaper's executive editor Sally Buzbee sent out a newsroom-wide memorandum directing employees to "Be constructive and collegial" in their interactions with colleagues.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2019, Covington Catholic High School student Nick Sandmann filed a defamation lawsuit against the *Post*, alleging that it libeled him in seven articles regarding the January 2019 Lincoln Memorial confrontation between Covington students and the Indigenous Peoples March.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] A federal judge dismissed the case, ruling that 30 of the 33 statements in the *Post* that Sandmann alleged were libelous were not, but allowed Sandmann to file an amended complaint as to three statements.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] After Sandmann's lawyers amended the complaint, the suit was reopened on October 28, 2019.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2020, *The Post* settled the lawsuit brought by Sandmann for an undisclosed amount.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Several *Washington Post* op-eds and columns have prompted criticism, including a number of comments on race by columnist Richard Cohen over the years, and a controversial 2014 column on campus sexual assault by George Will.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 2022, actor Johnny Depp successfully sued ex-wife Amber Heard for an op-ed she wrote in *The Washington Post* where she described herself as a public figure representing domestic abuse two years after she had publicly accused him of domestic violence.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Speaking on behalf of President Nixon, White House Press Secretary Ron Ziegler infamously accused *The Washington Post* of "shabby journalism" for their focus on Watergate only to apologize when the damning reporting on Nixon was proven correct.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] 45th/47th president Donald Trump repeatedly spoke out against *The Washington Post* on his Twitter account, having "tweeted or retweeted criticism of the paper, tying it to Amazon more than 20 times since his campaign for president" by August 2018.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In addition to often attacking the paper itself, Trump used Twitter to blast various *Post* journalists and columnists.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] During the 2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries, Senator Bernie Sanders repeatedly criticized *The Washington Post*, saying that its coverage of his campaign was slanted against him and attributing this to Jeff Bezos' purchase of the newspaper.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Sanders' criticism was echoed by the socialist magazine *Jacobin* and the progressive journalist watchdog Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] *Washington Post* executive editor Martin Baron responded by saying that Sanders' criticism was "baseless and conspiratorial".
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] A 2023 investigation by *The Intercept*, *The Nation*, and DeSmog found that *The Washington Post* creates and publishes advertising ("advertorial") for the fossil fuel industry.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Current journalists at *The Washington Post* include: Yasmeen Abutaleb, Dan Balz, Will Englund, Marc Fisher, Robin Givhan, David Ignatius, Ellen Nakashima, Ashley Parker, Sally Quinn, Michelle Singletary, Ishaan Tharoor, and Joe Yonan.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Former journalists of *The Washington Post* include: Scott Armstrong, Melissa Bell, Ann Devroy, Edward T.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Folliard, Malvina Lindsay, Mary McGrory, Christine Emba, Walter Pincus, and Bob Woodward.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Arc XP is a department of *The Washington Post*, which provides a publishing system and software for news and media organizations such as the *Boston Globe*, *Le Parisien*, *The Irish Times*, *Libération*, *Dallas Morning News*, The Globe and Mail, Record, Graham Media Group, and Sky News.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Mary Jordan was the founding editor, head of content, and moderator for *Washington Post Live*, the Post's editorial events business, which organizes political debates, conferences and news events for the media company.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] This includes "The 40th Anniversary of Watergate" in June 2012, that featured key Watergate figures including former White House counsel John Dean, *Washington Post* editor Ben Bradlee, and reporters Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein, which was held at the Watergate hotel.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Regular hosts include Frances Stead Sellers.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Lois Romano was formerly the editor of *Washington Post Live*.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1975, the Washington Post pressmen's union went on strike.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The *Post* hired replacement workers to replace the pressmen's union, and other unions returned to work in February 1976.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In 1986, during negotiations between the *Post* and the Newspaper Guild union over a new contract, five employees, including Newspaper Guild unit chairman Thomas R.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Sherwood and assistant Maryland editor Claudia Levy, sued the *Post* for overtime pay, stating that the newspaper had claimed that budgets did not allow for overtime wages.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] The petition followed on a year of unsuccessful negotiations between The Washington Post Guild and upper management over pay and benefit increases.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] Later the same month, the Washington Post Guild won a new three-year contract with the paper, ending 18 months of negotiations.
[src:compound-interest-website/washington-post] In May 2025, a majority of technology workers at the *Post* voted to unionize as the Washington Post Tech Guild, representing more than 300 engineering, product design, and data workers at the *Post*.
